## Task 5 SSH

- Server Authentication
SSH client checks server’s public key fingerprint.
Prevents man-in-the-middle attacks.
Once accepted, stored in known_hosts.
- Client Authentication
Methods: username/password (less secure) or SSH keys.
Keys generated with ssh-keygen (RSA, DSA, ECDSA, Ed25519).
Example: ssh-keygen -t ed25519.
Private key must remain secret; can be protected with passphrase.
Permissions must be strict (chmod 600).
- Security Context
authorized_keys contains allowed public keys.
In CTFs, adding a key to authorized_keys can serve as a backdoor.

